<subSubSection id="7ECD272B8E5DD8C37B54952F4CC3159A" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="874B343657FC234E9532CD6BACBF222A" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F20452665551C1DDE7EFB67B680CDA53" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
This genus with 18 species (
<bibRefCitation id="95755F36260CAE3CAF3DD440CAE86B25" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
) is included in 
<taxonomicName id="A225486111AF406FF2596E690E7B9391" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphothrips</taxonomicName>
genus-group (
<bibRefCitation id="C37ACE19BF5C6D662D1F7676A27B3980" author="Mound, LA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 76" title="Australian Thripinae of the Anaphothrips genus-group (Thysanoptera), with three new genera and thirty-three new species." volume="2042" year="2009">Mound and Masumoto 2009</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="5E417C0CB29255BC994A2B096644BD87" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Bhatti et al. (2003)</bibRefCitation>
published a catalogue of the 
<taxonomicName id="C1EA3645B1D9519A8CE8758D9664DA26" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eremiothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eremiothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eremiothrips</taxonomicName>
in Iran with key for separating the nine species of this genus. Recognition of species of 
<taxonomicName id="617BF6D87C6FE69EA3083F2F73991BA5" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eremiothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eremiothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eremiothrips</taxonomicName>
based on females is extremely difficult, since the general appearance and fine structural details of females are very similar in related species. However, males can be assigned readily to species because of distinctive structural features (
<bibRefCitation id="6931996D73D954DDA3983A31E8423D7D" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Bhatti et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
). In Iran, the genus includes 12 species (
<bibRefCitation id="45D7D1931E79A7FF5F73DC87B14BFA55" author="Bhatti, JS" journalOrPublisher="Thrips" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 23" title="Eremiothrips zurstrasseni, new species, from Khuzestan province in Iran (Insecta: Terebrantia: Thripidae)." volume="10" year="2009 b">Bhatti et al. 2009b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F2D8A8F0A8077960F5AD88D5CF871B9E" author="Ramezani, L" journalOrPublisher="Thrips" pageId="15" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 18" title="Discovery of Eremiothrips similis in Iran, with a catalogue of species of Eremiothrips in Iran (Insecta: Terebrantia: Thripidae)." volume="11" year="2009">Ramezani et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="23FC2242C50FD057370A22B4467BD5B3" author="Minaei, K" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="56 - 62" title="The genus Eremiothrips (Thysanoptera: Thripidae) in Iran, with one new species." volume="3349" year="2012 a">Minaei 2012a</bibRefCitation>
) and a key to Iranian 
<taxonomicName id="9FDADE309E51CD7F1CAC8B526DAABD96" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eremiothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eremiothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eremiothrips</taxonomicName>
based on the male sex is available (
<bibRefCitation id="6004DEF9A9250E2486F9C3665941E545" author="Minaei, K" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="56 - 62" title="The genus Eremiothrips (Thysanoptera: Thripidae) in Iran, with one new species." volume="3349" year="2012 a">Minaei 2012a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
